Concatenating, Joining and Merging¶

There are 3 main ways of combining DataFrames together: Concatenating, Joining and Merging. In this session we will discuss these 3 methods with examples.

Concatenating¶

Concatenation basically glues together DataFrames. Keep in mind that dimensions should match along the axis you are concatenating on.

The concat() function (in the main pandas namespace) does all of the heavy lifting of performing concatenation operations along an axis

You can use pd.concat() and pass in a list of DataFrames to concatenate together.

If .concat() with axis=0:

Keep in mind that unlike the append() and extend() methods of Python lists, the append() method in Pandas does not modify the original object instead, it creates a new object with the combined data. It also is not a very efficient method, because it involves creation of a new index and data buffer. Thus, if you plan to do multiple append operations, it is generally better to build a list of DataFrame s and pass them all at once to the concat() function.

Joining¶

Joining is a convenient method for combining the columns of two potentially differently-indexed DataFrames into a single result DataFrame.

Among the three DataFrame operations, join allows the lowest level of control. It will combine all the columns from the two tables. The way that rows from the two tables are combined is defined by how.

In [16]:
df_left = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['A0', 'A1', 'A2'],
                     'B': ['B0', 'B1', 'B2']},
                      index=['K0', 'K1', 'K2']) 

df_right = pd.DataFrame({'C': ['C0', 'C2', 'C3'],
                    'D': ['D0', 'D2', 'D3']},
                      index=['K0', 'K2', 'K3'])
In [17]:
df_left.join(df_right)
Out[17]:
A B C D
K0 A0 B0 C0 D0
K1 A1 B1 NaN NaN
K2 A2 B2 C2 D2

In [18]:
df_left.join(df_right, how='outer')
Out[18]:
A B C D
K0 A0 B0 C0 D0
K1 A1 B1 NaN NaN
K2 A2 B2 C2 D2
K3 NaN NaN C3 D3

In [19]:
df_left.join(df_right, how='inner')
Out[19]:
A B C D
K0 A0 B0 C0 D0
K2 A2 B2 C2 D2

If their are common columns, they are renamed with the defined lsuffix and rsuffix.

In [20]:
df_new = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['A00', 'A01', 'A02'],
                       'E': ['E00', 'E01', 'E02']},
                      index=['K0', 'K1', 'K2'])

df_new
Out[20]:
A E
K0 A00 E00
K1 A01 E01
K2 A02 E02
In [21]:
df_left.join(df_new, rsuffix = '_new')
Out[21]:
A B A_new E
K0 A0 B0 A00 E00
K1 A1 B1 A01 E01
K2 A2 B2 A02 E02
In [22]:
df_left.join(df_new, lsuffix = '_old')
Out[22]:
A_old B A E
K0 A0 B0 A00 E00
K1 A1 B1 A01 E01
K2 A2 B2 A02 E02

Merging¶

Pandas has full-featured, high performance in-memory join operations idiomatically very similar to relational databases like SQL. Pandas provides a single function, merge(), as the entry point for all standard database join operations between DataFrame objects

Similar to join, merge also combines all the columns from the two tables. However, merge provides three ways of flexible control over row-wise alignment.

  • The first way is to use on = COLUMN NAME, here the given column must be the common column in both tables.
  • The second way is to use left_on = COLUMN NAME and right_on = COLUMN NAME , and it allows to align the two tables using two different columns.
  • The third way is to use left_index = True and right_index = True, and the two tables are aligned based on their index.

Some of the useful arguments of a pd.merge() function:

  • left: A DataFrame
  • right: Another DataFrame
  • on: Column or index level names to join on. Must be found in both the left and right DataFrame.
  • how: One of 'left', 'right', 'outer', 'inner'. Defaults to inner. See below for more detailed description of each method.
  • left_on: Column or index level names to join on in the left DataFrame.
  • right_on: Column or index level names to join on in the right DataFrame.
  • left_index: Use the index from the left DataFrame as the join key.
  • right_index: Use the index from the right DataFrame as the join key.
  • suffixes : default is (_x, _y)

Advanced Example:¶

In [31]:
df1 = pd.DataFrame({'employee': ['Bob', 'Jake', 'Lisa', 'Sue'],
                    'group': ['Accounting', 'Engineering', 'Engineering', 'HR']})

df2 = pd.DataFrame({'employee': ['Lisa', 'Bob', 'Jake', 'Sue'],
                    'hire_date': [2004, 2008, 2012, 2014]})
In [32]:
df1
Out[32]:
employee group
0 Bob Accounting
1 Jake Engineering
2 Lisa Engineering
3 Sue HR
In [33]:
df2
Out[33]:
employee hire_date
0 Lisa 2004
1 Bob 2008
2 Jake 2012
3 Sue 2014
In [34]:
pd.concat([df1,df2])
Out[34]:
employee group hire_date
0 Bob Accounting NaN
1 Jake Engineering NaN
2 Lisa Engineering NaN
3 Sue HR NaN
0 Lisa NaN 2004.0
1 Bob NaN 2008.0
2 Jake NaN 2012.0
3 Sue NaN 2014.0
In [35]:
pd.merge(df1, df2)
Out[35]:
employee group hire_date
0 Bob Accounting 2008
1 Jake Engineering 2012
2 Lisa Engineering 2004
3 Sue HR 2014

The pd.merge() function recognizes that each DataFrame has an employee column, and automatically joins using this column as a key. The result of the merge is a new DataFrame that combines the information from the two inputs.

Additionally, keep in mind that the merge in general discards the index, except in the special case of merges by index.

In [36]:
df3 = pd.DataFrame({'name': ['Bob', 'Jake', 'Lisa', 'Sue'],
                    'salary': [70000, 80000, 120000, 90000]}) 

df3
Out[36]:
name salary
0 Bob 70000
1 Jake 80000
2 Lisa 120000
3 Sue 90000
In [37]:
pd.merge(df1, df3, left_on="employee", right_on="name")
Out[37]:
employee group name salary
0 Bob Accounting Bob 70000
1 Jake Engineering Jake 80000
2 Lisa Engineering Lisa 120000
3 Sue HR Sue 90000

The result has a redundant column that we can drop if desiredfor example, by using the drop() method of DataFrames

In [38]:
pd.merge(df1, df3, left_on="employee", right_on="name").drop('name', axis=1)
Out[38]:
employee group salary
0 Bob Accounting 70000
1 Jake Engineering 80000
2 Lisa Engineering 120000
3 Sue HR 90000

Sometimes, rather than merging on a column, you would instead like to merge on an index.

In [39]:
df1a = df1.set_index('employee')
df1a
Out[39]:
group
employee
Bob Accounting
Jake Engineering
Lisa Engineering
Sue HR
In [40]:
df2a = df2.set_index('employee')
df2a
Out[40]:
hire_date
employee
Lisa 2004
Bob 2008
Jake 2012
Sue 2014

The index can be used as the key for merging by specifying the left_index and/or right_index flags in pd.merge()

In [41]:
pd.merge(df1a, df2a, left_index=True, right_index=True)
Out[41]:
group hire_date
employee
Bob Accounting 2008
Jake Engineering 2012
Lisa Engineering 2004
Sue HR 2014

Sometimes, you may end up in a case where your two input DataFrames having conflicting column names.

df5 = pd.DataFrame({'name': ['Bob', 'Jake', 'Lisa', 'Sue'],'rank': [3, 1, 4, 2]})
In [43]:

1 Jake 2
2 Lisa 3
3 Sue 4
In [44]:

0 Bob 3
1 Jake 1
2 Lisa 4

0 Bob 1 3
1 Jake 2 1
2 Lisa 3 4
3 Sue 4 2

Summary¶

For pandas.DataFrame, both join and merge operates on columns and rename the common columns using the given suffix. In terms of row-wise alignment, merge provides more flexible control.

Different from join and merge, concat can operate on columns or rows, depending on the given axis, and no renaming is performed.
